VL  - 26
IS  - 2
SP  - 513
EP  - 580
DO  - 10.1007/s10459-020-09998-3
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-85092898343&doi=10.1007%2fs10459-020-09998-3&partnerID=40&md5=ecb47db36b419d85b759ed72c26408a4
AB  - Students as partners is a movement which is gaining momentum in higher education, yet disciplinary perspectives are underexplored. Using a qualitative synthesis approach informed by Major and Savin-Baden (2010), we systematically investigated how health professional education has taken up the practice of working in partnership with students. Fifty-five publications were identified in our search from 2011 to -mid 2018. The majority of literature came from North America and medicine was the most frequently represented health profession. Our three stage analysis identified five key themes: (1) framing (i.e. ethos) of the partnership; (2) drivers for partnership; (3) sustainability; (4) inclusion of student voice; and (5) understanding of partnership and its benefits and challenges. Health professional educators are well equipped to enact partnership opportunities due to their clinical skills in person-centred care. However to gain the most from student-staff partnerships, health professional education would benefit from greater awareness of the field’s theoretical understandings of partnership and its key principles of reciprocity, respect and responsibility. © 2020, Springer Nature B.V.
