TI  - Exploring cultural geography field course using story maps
PY  - 2019
T2  - Journal of Geography in Higher Education
VL  - 43
IS  - 2
SP  - 201
EP  - 223
DO  - 10.1080/03098265.2019.1597031
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-85063255077&doi=10.1080%2f03098265.2019.1597031&partnerID=40&md5=05c32e6812363d0b89fe71acc799dc7d
AB  - This article explores the use of Story Maps in a cultural geography field course that uses a place-based approach to understand the Delta Blue’s culture. In this study, Story Maps was used to capture and map student experiences as they engaged in a field study. Student experiences are captured by incorporating different data mediums such as narratives, personal reflections, digital photos, videos and website. Such a project has the potential to challenge students to work collectively and present a coherent story of their field experiences. This, in turn, can be used to improve the design and experience of a field course. The study demonstrates that the availability of simple web-based mapping platform such as Story maps provides students the ability to harness technology to create geocoded narratives, visual representations and spatial documentation to map their field course experience. © 2019, © 2019 Informa UK Limited, trading as Taylor & Francis Group.
